ata-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FCKNaD%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Median%20debt%20by%20age%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22450%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20that%20members%20of%20the%20elder%20millennial%20cohort%20hold%20a%20median%20of%20around%20%24140%2C000%20in%20debt%2C%20they%20only%20make%20a%20median%20of%20%2465%2C676%20a%20year%2C%20according%20to%20the%20latest%20earnings%20data%20from%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdata.bls.gov%2Fpdq%2FSurveyOutputServlet%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ECurrent%20Population%20Survey%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWorkers%20ages%2040%20to%2049%20hold%20around%20%244.4%20trillion%20in%20debt%2C%20per%20the%20Federal%20Reserve%20Bank%20of%20New%20York%20%E2%80%94%20the%20most%20of%20any%20age%20cohort%20they%20tracked.%20And%20that's%20also%20true%20for%20the%20youngest%20elder%20millennials%2C%20with%20workers%20ages%2030%20to%2039%20holding%20%243.9%20trillion%2C%20slightly%20outpacing%2050%20to%2059%20year%20olds.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat's%20not%20stopping%20elder%20millennials%20from%20spending%20money%20(or%20racking%20up%20credit%20card%20debt).%20A%20report%20from%20the%20Federal%20Reserve%20Bank%20of%20New%20York%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorkfed.org%2Fmedialibrary%2FResearch%2FInteractives%2FData%2Fequitable-growth-indicators%2Fdownloads%2F10_2023_EGI_national_consumer_spending.pdf%3Fsc_lang%3Den%26hash%3DCAECD9968CD2FA60AF8634493A507D71%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Efinds%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20Americans%20ages%2035%20to%2044%20are%20still%20spending%20on%20retail%20and%20restaurants%2C%20more%20so%20than%20their%20younger%20compatriots%20ages%2025%20to%2034.%20And%20while%20younger%20Americans%20are%20seeing%20more%20credit%20card%20debt%20go%20unpaid%20for%2090%20days%2C%20elder%20millennials%20are%20letting%20their%20debts%20languish%20too.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FP6oZS%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Transition%20into%20serious%20credit%20card%20delinquency%20by%20age%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22450%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EAt%20the%20same%20time%2C%20though%2C%20Americans%20under%2040%20are%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorkfed.org%2Fmedialibrary%2FResearch%2FInteractives%2FData%2Fequitable-growth-indicators%2Fdownloads%2F10_2023_EGI_national_wealth.pdf%3Fsc_lang%3Den%26hash%3DE49A671AEAC0EF96A14C4C2386EAAB84%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Eseeing%20their%20real%20wealth%20grow%20at%20a%20much%20faster%20rate%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E.%20And%2C%20while%20wage%20growth%20has%20been%20strong%20across%20all%20ages%2C%20it's%20been%20far%20more%20pronounced%20for%20workers%20under%2024.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2Fw0865%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Median%20wage%20growth%20by%20age%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22450%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EMeanwhile%2C%20the%20number%20of%20new%20foreclosures%20for%20those%20ages%2040%20to%2049%20has%20been%20ticking%20up%2C%20hitting%20around%208%2C800%20in%20the%20third%20quarter%20of%202023.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FD9vw7%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Foreclosures%20by%20age%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22